<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="221" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,1266,2013]" pageId="4" pageNumber="221">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,322,1338,1364]" pageId="4" pageNumber="221">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bowerbank" authorityYear="1864" box="[329,474,1339,1365]" class="Demospongiae" family="Hymedesmiidae" genus="Hymedesmia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Poecilosclerida" pageId="4" pageNumber="221" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[329,474,1339,1365]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="221">Hymedesmia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<emphasis box="[490,518,1339,1364]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="221">H.</emphasis>
) orange 
<emphasis box="[617,686,1339,1364]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="221">in situ</emphasis>
. Acanthostyles I echinating and acanthostyles II forming microconules at surface. Three categories of acanthostyles, bigger and intermediate ones partially spined, and smaller entirely spined (I. 262–360 × 7–10 µm; II. 118–231 × 3.5–10 µm; III. 65–106 x 2.6–6.1), tornotes (117–146 ×1.6–3µm), arcuate chelae (14.7–21.3 µm).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="223" pageId="4" pageNumber="221" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,1266,2013]" pageId="4" pageNumber="221">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,455,1482,1508]" pageId="4" pageNumber="221">
Description (
<figureCitation box="[352,442,1482,1508]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[178,1410,181,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-18@5.[178,1410,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Hymedesmia (H.) peruana sp. nov. A, live specimen (MNRJ 13694); B–C, skeleton architecture in transverse ground section; D, choanosomal acanthostyle I; E, choanosomal acanthostyle II; F, choanosomal acanthostyle III; G, ectosomal tornote; H–I, details of G; J–K, isochelae. Scale bars: A, 2 cm; B–C, 200 µm; D–G, 100 µm; H–I, 20 µm; J–K, 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6831771" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6831771/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="221">Fig. 3A</figureCitation>
).
</emphasis>
Thinly encrusting sponge (
<quantity box="[758,835,1483,1509]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.8" pageId="4" pageNumber="221" unit="cm" value="8.8">8.8 cm</quantity>
<superScript attach="left" box="[835,843,1482,1496]" fontSize="6" pageId="4" pageNumber="221">2</superScript>
), less than 
<quantity box="[968,1032,1483,1509]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="4" pageNumber="221" unit="mm" value="1.0">1 mm</quantity>
thick (
<quantity box="[1108,1281,1483,1509]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.8" metricValueMax="6.0" metricValueMin="1.6" pageId="4" pageNumber="221" unit="mm" value="0.38" valueMax="0.6" valueMin="0.16">0.16 to 0.6 mm</quantity>
). Consistency very soft and fragile. Surface smooth. Color in life orange (
<figureCitation box="[816,906,1519,1545]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[178,1410,181,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-18@5.[178,1410,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Hymedesmia (H.) peruana sp. nov. A, live specimen (MNRJ 13694); B–C, skeleton architecture in transverse ground section; D, choanosomal acanthostyle I; E, choanosomal acanthostyle II; F, choanosomal acanthostyle III; G, ectosomal tornote; H–I, details of G; J–K, isochelae. Scale bars: A, 2 cm; B–C, 200 µm; D–G, 100 µm; H–I, 20 µm; J–K, 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6831771" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6831771/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="221">Fig. 3A</figureCitation>
), turning to beige when preserved in ethanol.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,1266,2013]" pageId="4" pageNumber="221">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,462,1554,1580]" pageId="4" pageNumber="221">
Skeleton (
<figureCitation box="[319,449,1554,1580]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[178,1410,181,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-18@5.[178,1410,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Hymedesmia (H.) peruana sp. nov. A, live specimen (MNRJ 13694); B–C, skeleton architecture in transverse ground section; D, choanosomal acanthostyle I; E, choanosomal acanthostyle II; F, choanosomal acanthostyle III; G, ectosomal tornote; H–I, details of G; J–K, isochelae. Scale bars: A, 2 cm; B–C, 200 µm; D–G, 100 µm; H–I, 20 µm; J–K, 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6831771" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6831771/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="221">Figs 3B–C</figureCitation>
).
</emphasis>
Ectosomal skeleton with ectosomal strongyles forming bundles (4 to 7 spicules) extending up from the substrate. Choanosomal acanthostyles I may pierce the surface occasionally (
<figureCitation box="[1249,1337,1591,1617]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[178,1410,181,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-18@5.[178,1410,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Hymedesmia (H.) peruana sp. nov. A, live specimen (MNRJ 13694); B–C, skeleton architecture in transverse ground section; D, choanosomal acanthostyle I; E, choanosomal acanthostyle II; F, choanosomal acanthostyle III; G, ectosomal tornote; H–I, details of G; J–K, isochelae. Scale bars: A, 2 cm; B–C, 200 µm; D–G, 100 µm; H–I, 20 µm; J–K, 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6831771" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6831771/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="221">Fig. 3B</figureCitation>
). Subectosomal and choanosomal skeletons overlapping, with subectosomal canals (45–265 µm diameter). Choanosomal skeleton composed of typical hymedesmioid structure, consisting of a basal layer of spongin with acanthostyles I and II erect on the substrate (
<figureCitation box="[480,603,1699,1725]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[178,1410,181,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-18@5.[178,1410,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Hymedesmia (H.) peruana sp. nov. A, live specimen (MNRJ 13694); B–C, skeleton architecture in transverse ground section; D, choanosomal acanthostyle I; E, choanosomal acanthostyle II; F, choanosomal acanthostyle III; G, ectosomal tornote; H–I, details of G; J–K, isochelae. Scale bars: A, 2 cm; B–C, 200 µm; D–G, 100 µm; H–I, 20 µm; J–K, 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6831771" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6831771/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="221">Fig. 3B–C</figureCitation>
). Acanthostyles I pierce the ectosome and the acanthostyles II support the surface, forming microconules. Isochelae appear scattered in the ectosome, and some tylostyles lay parallel to, or flat on the substratum.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,1266,2013]" lastBlockId="6.[151,1437,150,357]" lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="223" pageId="4" pageNumber="221">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,595,1806,1833]" pageId="4" pageNumber="221">
Spicules (
<figureCitation box="[313,445,1806,1833]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[178,1410,181,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-18@5.[178,1410,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Hymedesmia (H.) peruana sp. nov. A, live specimen (MNRJ 13694); B–C, skeleton architecture in transverse ground section; D, choanosomal acanthostyle I; E, choanosomal acanthostyle II; F, choanosomal acanthostyle III; G, ectosomal tornote; H–I, details of G; J–K, isochelae. Scale bars: A, 2 cm; B–C, 200 µm; D–G, 100 µm; H–I, 20 µm; J–K, 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6831771" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6831771/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="221">Figs 3D–K</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[459,476,1806,1832]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1571,1595]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,381,1548]" captionTargetId="figure-116@6.[151,1435,381,1548]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 4. Hymedesmia (H.) peruana sp. nov. Bar plot illustrating the size frequency distribution obtained by the Sturges Algorithm for the acanthostyles (n = 100)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6831775" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6831775/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="221">4</figureCitation>
; 
<tableCitation box="[491,579,1806,1833]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="8.[151,239,612,638]" captionText="TABLE 1. Hymedesmia (Hymedesmia) spp. from Peru. Measurements (in µm) of the spicules (n = 30; unless stated otherwise in parentheses), length x thickness [as minimum– mean–maximum (± standard deviation)], distribution and bathymetry (in meters). Roman numerals correspond to size categories of acanthostyles.Abbreviations: Tor. (tornotes), Str. (strongyles), Sbty. (subtylotes), Tyl. (tyles), Sty. (styles), Ac. (arcuate chelae), Sig. (sigmas) and Mstr. (microstrongyles)." pageId="4" pageNumber="221">Table 1</tableCitation>
).
</emphasis>
Ectosomal diactines: tornotes, straight, isodiametric (
<figureCitation box="[1207,1298,1807,1833]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[178,1410,181,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-18@5.[178,1410,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Hymedesmia (H.) peruana sp. nov. A, live specimen (MNRJ 13694); B–C, skeleton architecture in transverse ground section; D, choanosomal acanthostyle I; E, choanosomal acanthostyle II; F, choanosomal acanthostyle III; G, ectosomal tornote; H–I, details of G; J–K, isochelae. Scale bars: A, 2 cm; B–C, 200 µm; D–G, 100 µm; H–I, 20 µm; J–K, 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6831771" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6831771/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="221">Fig. 3G</figureCitation>
), with conical extremities, 117– 
<emphasis box="[384,447,1843,1869]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="221">132.3</emphasis>
–146 (± 11.8) × 1.6– 
<emphasis box="[678,713,1843,1869]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="221">2.2</emphasis>
–2.9 (± 0.4) µm (
<figureCitation box="[906,1024,1843,1869]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[178,1410,181,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-18@5.[178,1410,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Hymedesmia (H.) peruana sp. nov. A, live specimen (MNRJ 13694); B–C, skeleton architecture in transverse ground section; D, choanosomal acanthostyle I; E, choanosomal acanthostyle II; F, choanosomal acanthostyle III; G, ectosomal tornote; H–I, details of G; J–K, isochelae. Scale bars: A, 2 cm; B–C, 200 µm; D–G, 100 µm; H–I, 20 µm; J–K, 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6831771" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6831771/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="221">Figs 3H–I</figureCitation>
). Choanosomal acanthostyles I (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[178,1410,181,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-18@5.[178,1410,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Hymedesmia (H.) peruana sp. nov. A, live specimen (MNRJ 13694); B–C, skeleton architecture in transverse ground section; D, choanosomal acanthostyle I; E, choanosomal acanthostyle II; F, choanosomal acanthostyle III; G, ectosomal tornote; H–I, details of G; J–K, isochelae. Scale bars: A, 2 cm; B–C, 200 µm; D–G, 100 µm; H–I, 20 µm; J–K, 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6831771" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6831771/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="221">Figs 3D</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[200,217,1879,1905]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1571,1595]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,381,1548]" captionTargetId="figure-116@6.[151,1435,381,1548]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 4. Hymedesmia (H.) peruana sp. nov. Bar plot illustrating the size frequency distribution obtained by the Sturges Algorithm for the acanthostyles (n = 100)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6831775" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6831775/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="221">4</figureCitation>
): hastate to acerate tip tapering gradually, rounded base; shaft straight, with spines occupying the basal two thirds of its length; spines mostly slightly curved, those of the base larger than those of the shaft, 262– 
<emphasis box="[1317,1380,1915,1941]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="221">300.7</emphasis>
–360 (± 34.3) × 7.7– 
<emphasis box="[332,367,1951,1977]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="221">8.3</emphasis>
–9.8 (± 0.8) µm. Choanosomal acanthostyles II (
<figureCitation box="[938,1032,1951,1977]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[178,1410,181,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-18@5.[178,1410,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Hymedesmia (H.) peruana sp. nov. A, live specimen (MNRJ 13694); B–C, skeleton architecture in transverse ground section; D, choanosomal acanthostyle I; E, choanosomal acanthostyle II; F, choanosomal acanthostyle III; G, ectosomal tornote; H–I, details of G; J–K, isochelae. Scale bars: A, 2 cm; B–C, 200 µm; D–G, 100 µm; H–I, 20 µm; J–K, 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6831771" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6831771/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="221">Figs 3E</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1048,1065,1951,1977]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1571,1595]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,381,1548]" captionTargetId="figure-116@6.[151,1435,381,1548]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 4. Hymedesmia (H.) peruana sp. nov. Bar plot illustrating the size frequency distribution obtained by the Sturges Algorithm for the acanthostyles (n = 100)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6831775" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6831775/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="221">4</figureCitation>
): similar to acanthostyles I, but slightly smaller, 118– 
<emphasis box="[390,453,1987,2013]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="221">182.7</emphasis>
–231 (± 40.3) × 3.5– 
<emphasis box="[679,714,1986,2012]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="221">6.5</emphasis>
–9.6 (± 2.0). Choanosomal acanthostyles III 
<emphasis box="[1205,1214,1987,2013]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="221">(</emphasis>
<figureCitation box="[1215,1298,1987,2013]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[178,1410,181,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-18@5.[178,1410,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Hymedesmia (H.) peruana sp. nov. A, live specimen (MNRJ 13694); B–C, skeleton architecture in transverse ground section; D, choanosomal acanthostyle I; E, choanosomal acanthostyle II; F, choanosomal acanthostyle III; G, ectosomal tornote; H–I, details of G; J–K, isochelae. Scale bars: A, 2 cm; B–C, 200 µm; D–G, 100 µm; H–I, 20 µm; J–K, 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6831771" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6831771/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="221">Figs 3F</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1308,1325,1987,2013]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1571,1595]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,381,1548]" captionTargetId="figure-116@6.[151,1435,381,1548]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 4. Hymedesmia (H.) peruana sp. nov. Bar plot illustrating the size frequency distribution obtained by the Sturges Algorithm for the acanthostyles (n = 100)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6831775" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6831775/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="221">4</figureCitation>
): straight, tapering gradually, acerate tip and rounded base, spined all over, 65.7– 
<emphasis box="[939,988,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="223">78.2</emphasis>
–106 (± 11.1) × 2.6– 
<emphasis box="[1218,1253,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="223">4.1</emphasis>
–6.1 (± 0.8) µm. Arcuate isochelae (
<figureCitation box="[366,487,187,213]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[178,1410,181,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-18@5.[178,1410,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Hymedesmia (H.) peruana sp. nov. A, live specimen (MNRJ 13694); B–C, skeleton architecture in transverse ground section; D, choanosomal acanthostyle I; E, choanosomal acanthostyle II; F, choanosomal acanthostyle III; G, ectosomal tornote; H–I, details of G; J–K, isochelae. Scale bars: A, 2 cm; B–C, 200 µm; D–G, 100 µm; H–I, 20 µm; J–K, 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6831771" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6831771/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="223">Figs 3J–K</figureCitation>
): one free spatulate ala and two lateral alae semi-fused with the shaft (
<figureCitation box="[1272,1362,187,213]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[178,1410,181,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-18@5.[178,1410,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Hymedesmia (H.) peruana sp. nov. A, live specimen (MNRJ 13694); B–C, skeleton architecture in transverse ground section; D, choanosomal acanthostyle I; E, choanosomal acanthostyle II; F, choanosomal acanthostyle III; G, ectosomal tornote; H–I, details of G; J–K, isochelae. Scale bars: A, 2 cm; B–C, 200 µm; D–G, 100 µm; H–I, 20 µm; J–K, 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6831771" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6831771/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="223">Fig. 3K</figureCitation>
), shaft characteristically curved, bow shaped, 14.7– 
<emphasis box="[650,699,222,248]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="223">16.4</emphasis>
–21.3 (± 1.4) µm.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
